segments.text: Well, it's not an issue.
I was just curious.
No, I don't really see it as being one.
I mean, there's never been a problem with anyone pointing out to me, and I don't see the resonance as, you know, starting an uprising.
I just don't see it that way.
Okay, that's fine.
You may not even have a feel for this.
When you were mentioning earlier about the early days, and that you were going around in these almost one-on-one educational...
This is something that came to me in my talk with Mr. Welles.

Do you think that because of the environment created here in the woodlands, that the woodlands, this may seem obvious, but does the woodlands preselect for a certain type of personality, a certain type of personality?
Someone with a built-in set of values.

What I'm getting at is, obviously, people from Winslow, Arizona, who've been born and raised in Winslow, Arizona, may not share our affinity for trees, you know, because they have a different life experience.

is part of the success of the Woodlands in that Mr. Mitchell, in his vision, has identified a set of values that appeal to a stratum or a type of personality or a type of actor that is different from, say, the person who moves to Kingwood or to any other surrounding.
development, which is more consonant with things that are going on, you know, from west coast to east coast to anywhere.
Do you understand what I'm asking?
I think that I don't think you can just zero in on one individual aspect.
I think it's everything that's going on in and around the woodlands has created a market.
I think it's, you know,
It's the school system.
It's the hearty toll road.
It's the community spirit kind of thing.

But to zero in even more, I mean, once you realize that, hey, I've got all of these qualities, these things that I can't get, I think as a whole that all of us are probably more at peace with our inner self
when we're in nature and close to nature.
I just think that's a quality that we all have.
Those that believe in God feel closer to God when they're walking in the woods.
For families, they like to go to nature.
They like to go to parks.
They like to go to trees.
And I just think it's, I think that aspect of what the Woodlands is all about is a strong, it's a strong card.
But I think you can't just have a block of woods and expect everyone to move there.
It's got to be easy to get there.
It's got to be a quality of life.
It's got to be a satisfaction that no one's going to be able to dump right next door to me.
It's that planned community.
So the package deal.
The whole is more important than some of this.
I think so.
But I think the draw of the nature aspect of it is a real strong draw.
Okay, I appreciate that.
The last question I think you've probably already answered.
and if there's something I should be asking you and I haven't because I'm not smart enough to figure it out.
Could you comment a little bit on the future of the woodlands as you see it environmentally?
Do you see, are there some things that keep you awake at night, that might keep you awake at night?
No.
I think, certainly not keeping me awake,
I don't think we know the outcome yet of what it's going to be on the wetlands issue.
It's a real big issue.
What's that?
I'm not familiar with that.
I'm not that familiar with it myself, but it's...
The definition of what is a wetlands and how that affects development in the wetlands?
Exactly.
President Bush made a statement and he's enforcing it through the Corps of Engineers and Fish and Wildlife that there be no
no net loss of those areas that are classified as wetlands.

And within a classification of wetlands, there's true wetlands that are wet, and there's things that are high and dry and growing pine trees that, because it has gray mottlings in the soil or something, may be classified as a wetland also.
So I'm not sure what that issue, how that's going to play out in the future development the next 10 or 15 years down the road.

interpreted strictly as I understand it today, all developers are going to have a hard time finding lands that are not classified as wetlands in large enough blocks that it's going to be very expensive to develop.
I think it's a big issue.
I think, to me, the future of the woodlands is brighter than it's ever been.
I just, so many things, many positive things are happening.
But I just think the good times are, it's going to get better.
We're just now beginning to see that the wilderness is getting large enough that it's going to perpetuate within itself more jobs and a better quality of living.
It's going to make it even more attractive for more people to move here.
So it's going to be, I would say, as long as it
the economy, whatever that is, allows it to, it's going to continue to grow at the rate that it has in the last few years.
I feel that.
I'm certainly not qualified to make that statement.
It's just a reaction.
Well, you've answered the question.
You're not worried about anything.
The wetlands is an issue.
You know, I sleep well at night, and I love my job, and I enjoy getting up and coming to the...
I probably have the only job that's that great.
Well, one of the advantages of your job is it gets done from time to time.
You can complete something, and you can come back off and take a look at it.
You can drive around and see, you know, some of the tasks around here are never-ending.
And we get lots of strokes, you know.
Yeah.
Everyone likes to be involved in something that, you take something that's unsightly, it's a construction site, and you turn it into something that everyone appreciates.
And they let you know about it, so it's a good feeling.
In the absence, something else just occurred to me as you were talking, in the absence of...
this codified environmental plan that we were mentioning earlier.
George Mitchell is 72.
The end of the woodlands is scheduled for sometime in 2020, 2030.
Unless Mr. Mitchell is more extraordinary than I think he is, he probably won't be around to see the end of the book.
He's very extraordinary.
Go ahead.
What I'm getting at, I guess, is when he should exit the scene for whatever reasons, what will happen to the book?
Will it march on the same?
Is the infrastructure such that it's got built-in resiliency?
Or will some change unspecified occur?
You know, what I'm trying to say is every corporation has its own culture.
The Woodlands Corporation and Mitchell Energy and Development is very much
the child of George Mitchell.
I mean, his personality permeates everything that goes on around here.
At least that's my sense of what's going on.
When that personality leaves the scene, what's going to happen?
It's going to be different.
Well, I wish I had asked that question.
I've thought about that often, and I think a lot of people have.
But I think it's something
I don't think anyone can answer that until we know more about who the players are going to be when he's not here.
He doesn't have a strong influence on the women to this point.
I think that's a good question and I hope we're around to see.
Things may change.
One of my fears is that,
that we won't be able to maintain the character of Horace.
We might not be able to maintain as I see it, as I feel it needs to be.
Because without his influence, we might be weak.

That's why I wondered, you know, when you mentioned, or that was actually the, why I asked that question is, if what you're doing is based in part upon folklore, you know, this is the way we've always done it, kind of thing, then what happens when, you know, you get hit by a truck or whatever happens, how does it continue on?
Who knows what's going on?
Where's the, you know, the institutional memory that's going to march on without the prison players?
Is there a constitution and bylaws and, you know, and are the values, in fact, you know, written down, carved in stone, whatever, so that others...
I think there are somewhat.
I think we'll always save the trees and the woodlands because that's the way development criteria has messed it up.
I mean, you legally cannot clear a tree off of your lot.
Well, and the very name says that, too.
I mean, yeah.
It's not very subtle.
Unless, let me finish, if it's under four inches or six inches.
I mean, if it's over four or six inches.
If it's under that, then it's debatable whether you can or not.
So that's where all the... That's where all the tension is.
That's where all the tension is, and that's where the debate is, and that's where the brush is.
Some of us want to clear it all out, and some of us want to save it.
That would be the only change, I think, after he's gone.
I think the people that live here would be, they would, I think...

rise to the occasion and battle the developer to whatever extent they could they tried to go the other way because of their concept of what the williams is all about because of their investment that they have here and a commitment to it i think it will so i i think it will it'll continue on maybe modify it somewhat to have a little bit more of a manicured look to it
Okay.
I don't want to take all your time, but I really appreciated your willingness to share your thoughts with me.
Is there something I should have asked?
I think you did a good job.
I'm not looking for a grade.
I'm just trying to get the information down that ought to be down.
No, I think we've covered everything.
I can't think of anything we've left out.
Well, good.
I appreciate it.
Okay.
